    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="746"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d746">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.51/6–746</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Mr. Henry Dearborn of the
                        Division of North cmd West Coast Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-07">June 7,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>—Mr. Briggs</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ABr1">A-Br</gloss>—Mr. Wright<note n="90"
                                xml:id="d746fn90">James H. Wright, Special Assistant to the
                                Assistant Secretary of State for American Republic Affairs.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_OFD1">OFD</gloss>—Mr. Luthringer</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ED1">ED</gloss>—Mr. Fetter<note n="91"
                                xml:id="d746fn91">Frank W, Fetter, Director of the Office of
                                Financial and Development Policy.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_ED1">ED</gloss>—Mr. Stenger<note n="92"
                                xml:id="d746fn92">Jerome J. Stenger, Special Assistant, Division of
                                Investment and Economic Development.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_NWC1">NWC</gloss>—Mr. Schnee</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <gloss target="#t_NWC1">NWC</gloss>—Mr. Dearborn</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>A meeting was held in Mr. Briggs’ office this morning to discuss our financial
                    relations with Ecuador. There was no meeting of the minds between <gloss
                        target="#t_OFD1">OFD</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>
                    officers present, except on the point that the <gloss target="#t_Eximbank1"
                        >Eximbank</gloss> should hold discussions with Ambassador Plaza <pb
                        facs="0896" n="878" xml:id="pg_878"/> in an attempt to reach an
                    understanding on the Bank’s over-all relationship with Eucador.</p>
                <p>Mr. Briggs and Mr. Wright reviewed numerous reasons why this Government should
                    assist Ecuador. Added to the usual points made, it was stressed that we were
                    trying to make it possible for the US Army to remain in the Galápagos, while we
                    were at the same time denying Ecuador economic help, and that this latter
                    attitude might well frustrate our efforts toward the desired military
                    arrangement. Mr. Briggs and Mr. Wright emphasized that, in their opinion, a
                    combination of all the factors involved justified US assistance to Ecuador at
                    this time.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_OFD1">OFD</gloss> representatives did not show any
                    inclination toward changing the position which they adopted prior to the turning
                    down of the H. T. Smith loan by the <gloss target="#t_Eximbank1"
                        >Eximbank</gloss> on June 5th. Mr. Luthringer stated that he saw no
                    possibility of any readjustment of our commitments to Ecuador which would make
                    it possible for us to extend credit both for the completion of the Manta-Quevedo
                    road and for the financing of the Smith proposal.</p>
            </div>
